    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much does JennAir appliance repair cost in Los Angeles?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Most JennAir repairs run $175–$580. Igniter replacement, door gasket, or cinematic LED driver are on the lower end. Culinary Center panel, V2 fan motor, or control board work runs higher. Diagnostic fee is $89, waived when you proceed. Written flat-rate estimate before work begins.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do you service both JennAir RISE and NOIR collections?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — both collections across all appliance types. RISE professional-style ranges with 25,000 BTU brass burners, and NOIR minimalist black-glass appliances with Obsidian interiors. Both use the Whirlpool platform for core components, with collection-specific finishes and electronics that require different handling during service.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can you repair JennAir NOIR without scratching the black glass?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — this is a specific part of our NOIR protocol. We apply protective covers to all adjacent surfaces before service, use non-abrasive tools only near the glass and Obsidian surfaces, and do a visual inspection before the job is complete. One scratch on NOIR black glass is immediately visible — we don't take that risk.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">My Culinary Center touchscreen has dead zones — is it the control board?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Most likely not. Culinary Center touch failures are usually panel-level — cooking steam condensation behind the glass disrupts the capacitive layer in specific zones. We test the control board separately to confirm before recommending parts. A panel replacement is usually one-third the cost of a full control board assembly.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">What is the V2 Vertical Dual-Fan convection and how does it fail?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">V2 uses two vertically-stacked convection fans to circulate heated air in a vertical pattern, eliminating the hot/cool spots single-fan ovens create. When one fan fails, baking becomes uneven top-to-bottom — a distinct pattern that tells us which component to test first. We test each fan motor independently before ordering parts.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Is JennAir part of Whirlpool?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — JennAir is a Whirlpool Corporation brand alongside KitchenAid, Maytag, and Amana. Current JennAir appliances share the Whirlpool platform for core components — control board families, sealed systems, sensor types. Our deep KitchenAid and Whirlpool experience translates directly to JennAir diagnostics and parts sourcing.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Do you repair JennAir's downdraft ventilation systems?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — JennAir invented downdraft ventilation in 1961 and it remains a signature product. Common failures: lift motor torque loss (causing slow or failed extension and retraction), grease accumulation blocking the lift mechanism track, and blower motor failure. We service the complete downdraft assembly including the lift motor, fan, filter, and duct connection.</div>
